Parliament, Wednesday, 26 September 2018 – The Portfolio Committees on Police and Public Works gave the management of the South African Police Service (SAPS) and Department of Public Works (DPW) 14 days to resolve the current security challenges at the national legislature. This after the committees were briefed on matters related to roles and responsibilities as well as safety and security at the Parliamentary precinct. The SAPS and DPW were called to Parliament following the tragic incident in which a senior staff member killed himself on 14 September 2018. The Chairperson of the Portfolio Committee on Police, Mr Francois Beukman, said that interim solutions were urgently required to address the immediate challenges of defunct metal detector scanners and security cameras at Parliament. The committees encouraged Parliament to learn from experiences of Parliaments in other countries with regard to safety and security. "We call on all Members of Parliament and staff to comply with the safety and security prescripts, and on Parliament to establish a stakeholder committee that will meet regularly to discuss safety issues,” said Mr Beukman. Lastly, the committees will invite the Joint Standing Committee on the Financial Management of Parliament, to its next meeting. ISSUED BY THE PARLIAMENTARY COMMUNICATION SERVICES ON BEHALF OF THE CHAIRPERSON OF THE PORTFOLIO COMMITTEE ON POLICE, MR FRANCOIS BEUKMAN. For media enquiries or interview with the Chairperson, please contact the Committee’s Media Officer: Name: Mr Justice Molafo
